  "text": "Django implements comprehensive SQL injection prevention through a multi-layered parameterization approach:\n\n## Raw SQL Query Handling\n\n### RawSQL Expression (expressions.py:1236-1269)\nThe RawSQL class allows developers to use raw SQL expressions while maintaining safety. It accepts SQL and params as separate arguments in __init__ (line 1239-1243) and returns them together in as_sql() (line 1248-1249), ensuring parameters are passed separately to the database driver.\n\n### raw() QuerySet Method (query.py:1461-1473)\nThe raw() method on QuerySet creates a RawQuerySet that accepts params=(). This method enforces parameter binding by passing params separately to RawQuerySet constructor (line 1467).\n\n### RawQuerySet Class (query.py:2210-2238)\nRawQuerySet stores params separately (line 2232) and passes them to a RawQuery object (line 2231), maintaining the separation between SQL and parameters.\n\n### RawQuery Class (sql/query.py:150-221)\nThe critical _execute_query method (lines 203-220) adapts parameters using connection.ops.adapt_unknown_value (line 209) and then calls cursor.execute(sql, params) with SQL and params as separate arguments (line 220). This is the key enforcement point for raw queries.\n\n## SQL Compilation and Parameterization\n\n### SQLCompiler Classes (sql/compiler.py)\nAll SQL compiler classes use parameterized queries:\n- SQLCompiler.execute_sql (line 1631): cursor.execute(sql, params)\n- InsertCompiler.execute_sql (line 1939): cursor.execute(sql, params)\n- UpdateCompiler.execute_sql (inherits from SQLCompiler)\n- DeleteCompiler.execute_sql (inherits from SQLCompiler)\n\nAll these methods first call self.as_sql() to separate SQL from params, then pass both separately to cursor.execute().\n\n## WHERE Clause and Filter Compilation\n\n### WhereNode.as_sql (sql/where.py:116-161)\nThe WhereNode compiles WHERE clauses by calling compiler.compile(child) for each filter condition (line 151), which returns (sql, params) tuples that are kept separate and extended into result_params list (line 159).\n\n### Lookup Classes (lookups.py)\nAll lookup classes implement as_sql() methods that:\n- BuiltinLookup.as_sql (line 237-242): Processes left-hand side and right-hand side with process_lhs() and process_rhs() methods, combining their params separately\n- FieldGetDbPrepValueMixin.get_db_prep_lookup (line 256-276): Calls Field.get_db_prep_value() to prepare values for database, returning placeholder '%s' and params as separate lists\n\n### Value Expression (expressions.py:1144-1195)\nThe Value expression wraps user-supplied values and ensures parameterization (line 1183: returns '%s', [val]) to prevent literal SQL injection from Python values.\n\n## Cursor Wrapper Layer\n\n### CursorWrapper (backends/utils.py:17-115)\nThe CursorWrapper class enforces parameterized execution:\n- execute() method (line 78-81): Delegates to _execute()\n- _execute() method (line 94-105): Calls self.cursor.execute(sql, params) with params as separate argument (line 105)\n\n### CursorDebugWrapper (backends/utils.py:117-163)\nMaintains the same parameterization in debug mode by calling super().execute(sql, params) (line 122), ensuring debugging doesn't bypass parameterization.\n\n## Database Operations\n\n### BaseDatabaseOperations (backends/base/operations.py)\n- quote_name() (line 413-420): Prevents SQL injection in identifiers by properly quoting table/column names\n- adapt_unknown_value() (line 550-567): Transforms Python values to database-compatible types before parameterization\n- last_executed_query() (line 284-306): Safely recreates the executed query for logging by replacing placeholders with adapted params (line 306)\n\n## Field Placeholder Support\n\n### Field.get_placeholder() (fields/__init__.py:2738+)\nField classes can override get_placeholder() to customize parameterization for specific field types, allowing backend-specific optimizations while maintaining safety.\n\n## Key Safety Principles\n\n1. **Separation of Concerns**: SQL and parameters are always kept as separate values throughout the execution chain\n2. **Placeholder System**: All dynamic values use '%s' or backend-specific placeholders rather than string concatenation\n3. **Parameter Adaptation**: The adapt_unknown_value() method ensures Python types are safely converted before being sent to the database\n4. **Cursor Wrapper Enforcement**: All database access goes through CursorWrapper, which enforces parameterized cursor.execute(sql, params) calls\n5. **No String Interpolation**: The codebase consistently avoids string formatting/interpolation for SQL, using only the parameterized API\n\nThis architecture ensures that even when developers use raw SQL queries, parameters are passed through the database driver's native parameterization mechanism, which is the industry standard for preventing SQL injection attacks."
